text: Explaining my depression to my mother, a conversation.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom, my depression is a shapeshifter.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: One day it is as small as a firefly in the palm of a bear.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: The next, it's the bear.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: On those days, I play dead until the bear leaves me alone.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I call the bad days the dark days.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom says try lighting candles.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: When I see a candle, I see the flesh of a church.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: The flicker of a flame sparks of a memory younger than noon.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I am standing beside her open casket.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: It is the moment I learn every person I ever come to know will someday die.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Besides, Mom, I'm not afraid of the dark.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Perhaps that's part of the problem.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom says, I thought the problem was that you can't get out of bed.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I can't.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Anxiety holds me a hostage inside of my house, inside of my head.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom says, where did anxiety come from?
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Anxiety is the cousin visiting from out of town.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Depression felt obligated to bring to the party.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom, I am the party.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Only I am a party I don't want to be at.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom says, why don't you try going to actual parties?
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: See your friends.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Sure, I make plans.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I make plans, but I don't want to go.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I make plans because I know I should want to go.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I know sometimes I would have wanted to go.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: It's just not that much fun having fun when you don't want to have fun, Mom.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: You see, mom, each night, insomnia sweeps me up in his arms, dips me in the kitchen in the small glow of the stove light.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Insomnia has this romantic way of making the moon feel like perfect company.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom says try counting sheep, but my mind can only count reasons to stay awake, so I go for walks.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: But my stuttering kneecaps clank like silver spoons held in strong arms with loose wrists.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: They ring in my ears like clumsy church bells, reminding me I am sleepwalking on an ocean of happiness I cannot baptize myself in.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom says happy is a decision.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: But my happy is as hollow as a pinpricked egg.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: My happy is a high fever that will break.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom says I am so good at making something out of nothing and then flat out asks me if I am afraid of dying.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: No, I am afraid of living.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom, I am lonely.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I think I learned how when dad left, how to turn the anger into lonely, the lonely into busy.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: So when I tell you I've been super busy lately,
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I mean, I've been falling asleep watching SportsCenter on the couch to avoid confronting the empty side of my bed, but my depression always drags me back to my bed until my bones are the forgotten fossils of a skeleton-sunken city, my mouth a boneyard of teeth broken from biting down on themselves, the hollow auditorium of my chest
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: swoons with echoes of a heartbeat, but I am a careless tourist here.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: I will never truly know everywhere I have been.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom still doesn't understand.
speaker: SPEAKER_00

text: Mom, can't you see that neither can I?
speaker: SPEAKER_00
